Date Sat 12 May 2012
Source: Sun Star Davao [edited]
http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/local-news/2012/05/12/death-villager-due-rabies-alarms-execs-221136


Death of villager due to rabies alarms administraters
--------------------------------------------
The City Veterinarian Office (CVO) was alarmed over the recent death of a villager due to rabies virus infection. Reports reaching the office said another villager in Barangay Balindog also died of the rabies virus infection. A 49-year-old resident died last week of rabies, data from the City Health Office said. The victim, according to his wife, was [bitten] by one of their puppies sometime in March this year [2012]. The puppy died the next day, the woman said. But her husband just shrugged his shoulders when told the dog might be rabid and that it might kill him. Last week, his wife said, her husband experienced fever, numbness, experienced discomfort and paralysis. Later, her husband had hallucinations and became hydrophobic.

When reports about the man's death reached the City Health Office and City Veterinarian Office, they immediately went to the victim's place and gave the family member doses of anti-rabies vaccine. They are still verifying reports that another resident of Barangay Balindog here died of rabies virus. Doctors at the hospital where the victim was treated and died eventually told the public to be extra cautious of dog bites as the animal might be a carrier of rabies virus. Rabies, they said, is a preventable disease that occurs in animals and attacks the brain, which might cause severe inflammation or encephalitis and death.

